Summary Statistics and Visualising Data

  • Databases are typically large!
  • We need ways to summarise or illustrate key features of the database
  • Such data summaries might take the form of…

    • quantities: mean / sd / range /min / max

    • plots: barcharts, boxplots,histograms,scatterplots

  • To compare between data groups we might make comparison tables, overlaid plots, or multiplot figures.

Palmer Penguins

Key details

  • The Palmer penguins database includes body measurements from three different species of penguin from three islands in Antarctica
  • The database is provided as an R package.
  • You can download the database using: install.packages("palmerpenguins")
  • You can then load in the package into your R work-space using:library(palmerpenguins)
  • And view the data using: head(penguins)

The variables

  • The variables stored for the penguins are:
  • species
  • island
  • bill_length_mm
  • bill_depth_mm
  • flipper_length_mm
  • body_mass_g
  • sex
  • year

  • Objective:

  • In this notebook, you will load the Palmer Penguins dataset and demonstrate how to use R for generating summary statistics and visualizations. Your goal is to elucidate the key features of the dataset and the distinctions between penguin species.

  • Steps:

  • Install the Necessary Package:

  • To access the data, you need to install the palmerpenguins package. This is done by running install.packages("palmerpenguins") in the R console window. Note that this command is not included in the Notebook as it only needs to be executed once.

Load the Data:
